<TITLE> WI 56-1 at stumps, Tigers 232 all out </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 18 (bdnews24.com)  West Indies were 56 for one, a lead of 61 at stumps on the second day of the second and final Test against Bangladesh in St George's, Grenada on Saturday. The home side lost opener Dale Richards leg before to Shakib Al Hasan after he put on 20 runs for the first wicket. At the close, Travis Dowlin and Omar Philips were undefeated on 23 and 17 respectively. Earlier, a superb exhibition of pace bowling by Kemar Roach left Bangladesh five runs short of the home side's first innings total of 237. The 21-year-old one of seven debutants playing for the hosts as result of a boycott by their leading players, grabbed the three remaining wickets to finish with 6-48. After claiming the final wicket -- Mahmudullah Riyad who resisted for 82 balls before being caught for 28 attempting to hook the bowler  Roach led his team-mates off the National Cricket Stadium ground. Before that the West Indian paceman ended a stubborn 62-run eighth stand between Mushfiqur Rahim (47) and Mahmudullah. The pair, who came together with the score on 157-7, was separated after Roach induced Rahim into chasing a widish delivery, but the Bangladesh wicketkeeper-batsman only managed a thick edge to the keeper. Four runs later, tailender Shahadat Hossain became his fifth wicket when he was caught at second 
